<p:sld xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/presentationml/2006/main"><p:cSld><p:spTree><p:nvGrpSpPr><p:cNvPr id="1" name=""/><p:cNvGrpSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvGrpSpPr><p:grpSpPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="0" y="0"/><a:ext cx="0" cy="0"/><a:chOff x="0" y="0"/><a:chExt cx="0" cy="0"/></a:xfrm></p:grpSpPr><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="2" name="Title 1"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{0B229C1A-A81A-7FFA-04A7-E53B1EDAD7D3}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="title"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Presentations to senior management can be quite tricky, so here are a few more tips (2/2)</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="3" name="Content Placeholder 2"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{C70489A3-2583-6D9B-F661-D295DBFA4DAD}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph idx="1"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="838200" y="1825625"/><a:ext cx="10515600" cy="4898082"/></a:xfrm></p:spPr><p:txBody><a:bodyPr><a:normAutofit/></a:bodyPr><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Prepare a lot, practice a little</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Senior management tend to ask questions and go on detours, so expect to go off-track from your presentation or to go back and forth. To do this well and to adjust accordingly, you need to be very familiar with all the work you’ve done, especially the context and methodology, and practice how to explain things on the fly.</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t> </a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Answer directly and honestly</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Don’t give evasive answers in response to difficult questions. Senior management are usually well-trained to detect when people are hiding problems from them. Explain any problems or challenges faced in a fair, objective, data-driven manner.</a:t></a:r><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" i="1" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Make your ask / recommendation explicit</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Another common mistake is to go into a meeting without a clear goal, which is a missed opportunity considering you have the undivided attention from senior management. Ensure your asks or recommendations are very clear in your deck, and make sure to restate them again at the end.</a:t></a:r><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" i="1" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="4" name="TextBox 3"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{A2613B3E-328D-F6AE-7C53-46620BD2AEAC}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr txBox="1"/><p:nvPr/></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="5992836" y="6262042"/><a:ext cx="5219115" cy="461665"/></a:xfrm><a:prstGeom prst="rect"><a:avLst/></a:prstGeom><a:noFill/></p:spPr><p:txBody><a:bodyPr wrap="square" rtlCol="0"><a:spAutoFit/></a:bodyPr><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:pPr algn="r"/><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="1200" i="1" dirty="0"><a:latin typeface="Helvetica" pitchFamily="2" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Many of these are learnt from experience and also taken from “An Elegant Puzzle: Systems of Engineering Management” by Will Larson</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree><p:extLst><p:ext uri="{BB962C8B-B14F-4D97-AF65-F5344CB8AC3E}"><p14:creationId xmlns:p14="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2010/main" val="1987757528"/></p:ext></p:extLst></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:sld>